#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:152
msgid "Labeling tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:154
msgid ""
"Unlabeled tests like the ones above are run in the default ``numpy.test()`` "
"run.  If you want to label your test as slow - and therefore reserved for a "
"full ``numpy.test(label='full')`` run, you can label it with ``pytest.mark."
"slow``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:159
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.slow\n"
"def test_big(self):\n"
"    print('Big, slow test')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:165
msgid "Similarly for methods::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:167
msgid ""
"class test_zzz:\n"
"    @pytest.mark.slow\n"
"    def test_simple(self):\n"
"        assert_(zzz() == 'Hello from zzz')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:173
msgid "Easier setup and teardown functions / methods"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:175
msgid ""
"Testing looks for module-level or class method-level setup and teardown "
"functions by name; thus::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:178
msgid ""
"def setup_module():\n"
"    \"\"\"Module-level setup\"\"\"\n"
"    print('doing setup')\n"
"\n"
"def teardown_module():\n"
"    \"\"\"Module-level teardown\"\"\"\n"
"    print('doing teardown')\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class TestMe:\n"
"    def setup_method(self):\n"
"        \"\"\"Class-level setup\"\"\"\n"
"        print('doing setup')\n"
"\n"
"    def teardown_method():\n"
"        \"\"\"Class-level teardown\"\"\"\n"
"        print('doing teardown')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:197
msgid ""
"Setup and teardown functions to functions and methods are known as "
"\"fixtures\", and they should be used sparingly. ``pytest`` supports more "
"general fixture at various scopes which may be used automatically via "
"special arguments.  For example,  the special argument name ``tmpdir`` is "
"used in test to create a temporary directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:204
msgid "Parametric tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:206
msgid ""
"One very nice feature of testing is allowing easy testing across a range of "
"parameters - a nasty problem for standard unit tests. Use the ``pytest.mark."
"parametrize`` decorator."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:211
msgid "Doctests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:213
msgid ""
"Doctests are a convenient way of documenting the behavior of a function and "
"allowing that behavior to be tested at the same time.  The output of an "
"interactive Python session can be included in the docstring of a function, "
"and the test framework can run the example and compare the actual output to "
"the expected output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:219
msgid ""
"The doctests can be run by adding the ``doctests`` argument to the "
"``test()`` call; for example, to run all tests (including doctests) for "
"numpy.lib::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:223
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> np.lib.test(doctests=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:226
msgid ""
"The doctests are run as if they are in a fresh Python instance which has "
"executed ``import numpy as np``. Tests that are part of a NumPy subpackage "
"will have that subpackage already imported. E.g. for a test in ``numpy/"
"linalg/tests/``, the namespace will be created such that ``from numpy import "
"linalg`` has already executed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:234
msgid "``tests/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:236
msgid ""
"Rather than keeping the code and the tests in the same directory, we put all "
"the tests for a given subpackage in a ``tests/`` subdirectory. For our "
"example, if it doesn't already exist you will need to create a ``tests/`` "
"directory in ``numpy/xxx/``. So the path for ``test_yyy.py`` is ``numpy/xxx/"
"tests/test_yyy.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:242
msgid ""
"Once the ``numpy/xxx/tests/test_yyy.py`` is written, its possible to run the "
"tests by going to the ``tests/`` directory and typing::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:245
msgid "python test_yyy.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:247
msgid ""
"Or if you add ``numpy/xxx/tests/`` to the Python path, you could run the "
"tests interactively in the interpreter like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:250
msgid ""
">>> import test_yyy\n"
">>> test_yyy.test()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:254
msgid "``__init__.py`` and ``setup.py``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:256
msgid ""
"Usually, however, adding the ``tests/`` directory to the python path isn't "
"desirable. Instead it would better to invoke the test straight from the "
"module ``xxx``. To this end, simply place the following lines at the end of "
"your package's ``__init__.py`` file::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:261
msgid ""
"...\n"
"def test(level=1, verbosity=1):\n"
"    from numpy.testing import Tester\n"
"    return Tester().test(level, verbosity)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:266
msgid ""
"You will also need to add the tests directory in the configuration section "
"of your setup.py::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:269
msgid ""
"...\n"
"def configuration(parent_package='', top_path=None):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    config.add_subpackage('tests')\n"
"    return config\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:276
msgid "Now you can do the following to test your module::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:278
msgid ""
">>> import numpy\n"
">>> numpy.xxx.test()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:281
msgid ""
"Also, when invoking the entire NumPy test suite, your tests will be found "
"and run::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:284
msgid ""
">>> import numpy\n"
">>> numpy.test()\n"
"# your tests are included and run automatically!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:289
msgid "Tips & Tricks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:292
msgid "Creating many similar tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:294
msgid ""
"If you have a collection of tests that must be run multiple times with minor "
"variations, it can be helpful to create a base class containing all the "
"common tests, and then create a subclass for each variation. Several "
"examples of this technique exist in NumPy; below are excerpts from one in "
"`numpy/linalg/tests/test_linalg.py <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/blob/main/"
"numpy/linalg/tests/test_linalg.py>`__::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:301
msgid ""
"class LinalgTestCase:\n"
"    def test_single(self):\n"
"        a = array([[1., 2.], [3., 4.]], dtype=single)\n"
"        b = array([2., 1.], dtype=single)\n"
"        self.do(a, b)\n"
"\n"
"    def test_double(self):\n"
"        a = array([[1., 2.], [3., 4.]], dtype=double)\n"
"        b = array([2., 1.], dtype=double)\n"
"        self.do(a, b)\n"
"\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"class TestSolve(LinalgTestCase):\n"
"    def do(self, a, b):\n"
"        x = linalg.solve(a, b)\n"
"        assert_allclose(b, dot(a, x))\n"
"        assert imply(isinstance(b, matrix), isinstance(x, matrix))\n"
"\n"
"class TestInv(LinalgTestCase):\n"
"    def do(self, a, b):\n"
"        a_inv = linalg.inv(a)\n"
"        assert_allclose(dot(a, a_inv), identity(asarray(a).shape[0]))\n"
"        assert imply(isinstance(a, matrix), isinstance(a_inv, matrix))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:326
msgid ""
"In this case, we wanted to test solving a linear algebra problem using "
"matrices of several data types, using ``linalg.solve`` and ``linalg.inv``.  "
"The common test cases (for single-precision, double-precision, etc. "
"matrices) are collected in ``LinalgTestCase``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:332
msgid "Known failures & skipping tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:334
msgid ""
"Sometimes you might want to skip a test or mark it as a known failure, such "
"as when the test suite is being written before the code it's meant to test, "
"or if a test only fails on a particular architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:338
msgid "To skip a test, simply use ``skipif``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:340
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(SkipMyTest, reason=\"Skipping this test because...\")\n"
"def test_something(foo):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:346
msgid ""
"The test is marked as skipped if ``SkipMyTest`` evaluates to nonzero, and "
"the message in verbose test output is the second argument given to "
"``skipif``.  Similarly, a test can be marked as a known failure by using "
"``xfail``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:351
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.xfail(MyTestFails, reason=\"This test is known to fail "
"because...\")\n"
"def test_something_else(foo):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:357
msgid ""
"Of course, a test can be unconditionally skipped or marked as a known "
"failure by using ``skip`` or ``xfail`` without argument, respectively."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:360
msgid ""
"A total of the number of skipped and known failing tests is displayed at the "
"end of the test run.  Skipped tests are marked as ``'S'`` in the test "
"results (or ``'SKIPPED'`` for ``verbose > 1``), and known failing tests are "
"marked as ``'x'`` (or ``'XFAIL'`` if ``verbose > 1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:367
msgid "Tests on random data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:369
msgid ""
"Tests on random data are good, but since test failures are meant to expose "
"new bugs or regressions, a test that passes most of the time but fails "
"occasionally with no code changes is not helpful. Make the random data "
"deterministic by setting the random number seed before generating it.  Use "
"either Python's ``random.seed(some_number)`` or NumPy's ``numpy.random."
"seed(some_number)``, depending on the source of random numbers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:376
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can use `Hypothesis`_ to generate arbitrary data. "
"Hypothesis manages both Python's and Numpy's random seeds for you, and "
"provides a very concise and powerful way to describe data (including "
"``hypothesis.extra.numpy``, e.g. for a set of mutually-broadcastable shapes)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../TESTS.rst:381
msgid ""
"The advantages over random generation include tools to replay and share "
"failures without requiring a fixed seed, reporting *minimal* examples for "
"each failure, and better-than-naive-random techniques for triggering bugs."
msgstr ""

